{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489310"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:12:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:12:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"631"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/631"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.27,0.04,0.2,0.46]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"631"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50773"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/631"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"631"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36004"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"100"},{"type":"tags","id":"2062"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14025"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50773"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man is starting a course of outpatient chemotherapy for a recently diagnosed small cell carcinoma of the lung. Consideration is being given to assess his venous thromboembolism risk. He has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. His body mass index is 24 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. He mobilises independently and is independent in all activities of daily living.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory tests performed are summarised as below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 110 g/L (135-180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 9 g/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 285 g/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following regimens would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Warfarin","Enoxaparin","Unfractionated heparin","Rivaroxaban","No VTE prophylaxis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EActive malignancy is a strong risk factor for venous thromboembolism (VTE). The risk is further increased when patients are hospitalised with acute illnesses resulting in reduced mobility. Hence, most patients with active malignancy who are hospitalised with acute illnesses require pharmacological VTE prophylaxis in the absence of significant contraindications. The common options are low-molecular-weight heparin (e.g., \u003Cstrong\u003Eenoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E, dalteparin), and \u003Cstrong\u003Eunfractionated heparin\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn contrast, most outpatients with active malignancy who are ambulatory do not require pharmacological VTE prophylaxis. A commonly used risk assessment tool is the Khorana score. This takes into account:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESite of cancer:\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Every high risk (stomach, pancreas): 2 points\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehigh risk (lung, gynaecological, bladder, testicular, or lymphoma): 1 point\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Col start=\u00222\u0022\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPre-chemotherapy blood counts:\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eplatelet count of \u2265350 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L: 1 point\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehaemoglobin of \u0026lt;100 g/L or requiring red blood cell growth factors: 1 point\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eleucocyte count of \u0026gt;11\u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L: 1 point\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Col start=\u00223\u0022\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBody mass index\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u226535 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E: 1 point\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe VTE risk is stratified according to the total score to high (\u22653 points), intermediate (1-2 points), low (0 points). Pharmacological VTE prophylaxis is recommended in high-risk patients, and some patients with a risk score of 2. This patient has a risk score of 1, hence VTE prophylaxis is not required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect-acting oral anticoagulants (DOACs), including \u003Cstrong\u003Erivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E, and apixaban can be used for preventing VTE in patients post-hip or knee replacement. They are also used as therapeutic anticoagulants in patients with atrial fibrillation and VTE. \u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is a vitamin K antagonist used for therapeutic rather than prophylactic anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most patients with active malignancy who are hospitalised require chemical VTE prophylaxis in the absence of any contraindications.","In contrast, most outpatients who are ambulatory do not require pharmacological VTE prophylaxis.","Common pharmacological VTE prophylaxis options are low-molecular-weight heparin (e.g., enoxaparin, dalteparin), and unfractionated heparin."],"references":["Key NS, Khorana AA, Kuderer NM, Bohlke K, Lee AYY, et al. Venous Thromboembolism Prophylaxis and Treatment in Patients With Cancer: ASCO Clinical Practice Guideline Update. J Clin Oncol. 2020;38(5):496-520. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31381464/","Khorana AA, Kuderer NM, Culakova E, Lyman GH, Francis CW. Development and validation of a predictive model for chemotherapy-associated thrombosis. Blood. 2008 May 15;111(10):4902\u20137."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36004"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"631"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36004"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-17T07:24:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-17T07:25:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"631"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50773"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.